{"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"duration_ms":135075,"duration_api_ms":227071,"num_turns":6,"result":"","stop_reason":"end_turn","session_id":"a7ecb6c1-d07f-4d9c-a7a8-8ef2e1fecf1a","total_cost_usd":0.71190435,"usage":{"input_tokens":4,"cache_creation_input_tokens":40502,"cache_read_input_tokens":69408,"output_tokens":3326,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":40502,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"},"modelUsage":{"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001":{"inputTokens":294,"outputTokens":14942,"cacheReadInputTokens":1484501,"cacheCreationInputTokens":93951,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":0.34089284999999997,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":32000},"claude-opus-4-6":{"inputTokens":4,"outputTokens":3326,"cacheReadInputTokens":69408,"cacheCreationInputTokens":40502,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":0.3710115,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":64000}},"permission_denials":[],"structured_output":{"summary":"All four amendments identify real issues. Three are clear accepts for concrete correctness or safety bugs. The fourth (fr-9-f4e1cccb) is nuanced — the fallback's Tier 2 logic doesn't account for concurrently running rows with different run_ids, which can silently rewrite the wrong attempt in mixed legacy/corrupt state — but is still a valid accept because it violates the documented contract's \"reject ambiguous\" requirement.","votes":[{"amendment_id":"fr-9-f0ca9b46","decision":"accept","rationale":"Verified: `CompletionJournalDetails::render()` (fs.rs:2347-2360) and `completion_event_details()` (service.rs:239-252) are structurally identical but independently maintained. The repair path in `repairable_completion_event` round-trips through parse→merge→render, so any format drift between the two sites will cause the parse to fail silently, falling through to duplicate appends instead of backfilling. Consolidating into a single shared function is the correct fix — it eliminates a real silent-failure mode with no downside."},{"amendment_id":"fr-9-1fa4f2f8","decision":"accept","rationale":"Verified: `split_required` uses `split_once(\", \")` on project_id, run_id, and plan_hash fields with no upstream validation that these values are delimiter-free. The trailing `detail` field is correctly handled via `split_once(\", detail=\")`, but the intermediate fields rely on an undocumented invariant. The amendment's ask is modest — a code comment or debug_assert — and correctly identifies a real hidden assumption. Adding documentation/assertions is cheap insurance against future breakage if identifier formats ever evolve."},{"amendment_id":"fr-9-f4e1cccb","decision":"accept","rationale":"Verified: Tier 2 fallback (fs.rs ~line 2821-2832) filters for entries where run_id is None AND outcome is non-terminal, then accepts if exactly one such entry exists. But it does NOT check whether other running entries with *different* run_ids coexist for the same bead/project. In the described scenario ([run_id=None, running] + [run_id=run-2, running]), calling update with run_id=run-3 finds exactly one runless running row and claims it — even though the presence of a concurrent run-2 running row makes the assignment ambiguous. The documented contract (service.rs:107-109) explicitly requires rejecting ambiguous matches. The Tier 2 filter should additionally verify no other running rows exist for the same bead/project before accepting the lone runless row."},{"amendment_id":"fr-9-6ff93073","decision":"accept","rationale":"Verified: `collapse_task_run_attempts()` (model.rs:431-468) iterates terminal entries and pairs each with a matching non-terminal start. Two identical terminal rows for the same attempt are both terminal, so neither qualifies as a 'start' to consume — both pass through to the output unchanged. While the write path in `update_task_run` actively deduplicates during updates, `find_runs_for_bead` (fs.rs:3007-3024) only calls `collapse_task_run_attempts` at read time, so pre-existing duplicate terminal rows in NDJSON (from crashes, manual edits, or replays that bypassed the write dedup) will be reported as separate entries. This overstates retries/outcomes in the audit query. The collapse function should also deduplicate repeated terminal rows for the same attempt."}]},"fast_mode_state":"off","uuid":"7c75996d-fb45-4574-8610-fd7a5d0a9e7f"}
